2026-04-21 01:27:11 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load-module series protection diode'] hypothesis_explanation='All tests show the power-supply module is stable at ~11.8–12 V and its LED is steadily on. The ambient sensor module output is also steady: the relay coil has equal voltage on both ends (no switching), the relay contacts measure closed with ~0 Ω and ~11.85 V on both sides, and the control-module output cables to the load remain at constant polarity and voltage. So the 20 s / 0.5 s outages are not originating from the supply or the control module.\n\nWithin the load module, measurements confirm correct polarity and a constant ~11.8 V at the input. The brief outages appear only as a change in the voltage across the series protection diode: during each 0.5 s event, the drop across this diode shifts to about 0.77 V, so the lamp still sees ~11.06 V (i.e., there is no genuine supply interruption). The external symptom is that the lamp visibly turns off for 0.5 s, yet the upstream voltage is steady. The only component whose state is changing in sync with the visual effect, and which sits between the stable supply and the lamp, is the series diode.\n\nA diode that is internally intermittent (e.g., due to microcracks, thermal effects, or marginal junction behavior) can enter a high-impedance or erratic conduction state under certain current or temperature conditions. In a simulator this can manifest as a non-convergent or oscillatory solution, exactly as reported. Such an intermittent or partially open series diode would cause the lamp current to collapse periodically even though the measured DC voltage level before/after it seems only slightly altered, because the meter averages or loads the circuit differently than the lamp.\n\nSince no other component or wiring shows any corresponding voltage drop or switching action, the most plausible single-point root cause is a faulty series protection diode in the load module. Replacing this diode should eliminate the periodic lamp outages while leaving the rest of the system unchanged.'
